SVR is the regression version of Support Vector Machine (SVM).

Instead of finding a line that passes through every point, SVR tries to find a line (or curve) where most points fall within a certain acceptable error margin.

If prediction is close enough,
I don't care about the error.
This acceptable region is called:
        Epsilon Tube (ε)

                 *
      *

------------------  Upper Boundary

==================  Regression Line

------------------  Lower Boundary

            *
   *

Points inside the tube:
    No penalty

Points outside:
    Penalty
    Only the points outside or touching the boundary influence the model.
    These points are called: Support Vectors

Why is it Called Support Vector Regression?

Because only the support vectors determine the regression function.

Most data points do not directly affect the model.

| Linear Regression     | SVR                           |
| --------------------- | ----------------------------- |
| Fits all points       | Uses support vectors          |
| Minimizes total error | Ignores small errors inside ε |
| Straight line         | Linear or nonlinear           |
| Scaling optional      | Scaling required              |
| Fast                  | Slower                        |

Why is Feature Scaling mandatory?

SVR is distance-based and sensitive to feature magnitudes, so features must be scaled before training.

why feature scaling is most important for support vector regression?
SVR is a distance-based algorithm.

Feature scaling is important because SVR calculates:
    Distances
    Margins
    Kernel Similarities
If features have different scales, one feature dominates the distance calculation.


What is Feature Scaling?

Feature Scaling is the process of bringing all features to a similar range so that no feature dominates others because of its magnitude.

when it comes to dependent variables you don't have to apply feature scaling when if it is already in the range. for a example if we already applied encoding category variable which label encoding 

